        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">According to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7811.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Trenn 1974</ref>, p. 480 n. 87, this is probably the co-embedded specimen of <hi rend="italic">Pollicipes glaber</hi> from the Chalk described in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2621.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Fossil Cirripedia</hi> (1851): </ref>62 and Tab. III, fig. 10a.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD began systematic descriptions of the sessile Cirripedia on 28 April 1850 (see ‘Journal’; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 4, Appendix I).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1680.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edward Forbes</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Bowerbank had initiated in 1847 the establishment of the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3646.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Palaeontographical Society</ref> for the purpose of publishing undescribed British fossils (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2063.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">DNB</hi></ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_352.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henrick Henricksen Beck</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
